<BR><DIV CLASS="c5"><P CLASS="c6"><SPAN CLASS="c7">Bloomberg on </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c11">Sean Bell</SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c7"> Officers</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c5"><P CLASS="c6"><SPAN CLASS="c8">BYLINE: </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2">Observer Staff</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c5"><P CLASS="c6"><SPAN CLASS="c8">LENGTH: </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2">92 words</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c5"><P CLASS="c9"><SPAN CLASS="c2">At his first public appearance since three police officers were indicted in the </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c4">Sean Bell</SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2"> killing, the mayor clarified his position on the conduct of the police that night.</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c9"><SPAN CLASS="c2">At a press conference on the West Side, Bloomberg told reporters he never said &quot;anybody broke the law. It's not my job to decide whether somebody broke a law. And, you know, I made my comments as a civilian.&quot;</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c9"><SPAN CLASS="c2">The civilian &quot;comments&quot; he's referring to were made the day after the shooting in the Blue Room, when Bloomberg said he thought police used &quot;excessive&quot; force.-- Azi Paybarah </SPAN></P>
</DIV>
